About

Motivation: explore different model building strategies for covariate selection.

Main points:

  • Employ bayesian model averaging (implemented in SOLAR, See tutorial, Section 6.6.2 Bayesian Model Averaging with Covariates) for covariate selection.
    • Fix secure covariates: Age and Sex, when it is the case.
  • Pre-process Age covariate by both centering and scaling (named as Agesc, where sc means scaled).
  • Mantain two protocols: with & without Height and Weight covariates.

Models

  1. Model protocol as in the last paper submission, i.e.all covariates are put into the base model and then screening is applied.
  2. Bayesian model averaging + Age and Sex fixed.
  3. Bayesian model averaging + Age and Sex fixed + Weight + Height.

Note that Models 1 and 2 does not include Height and Weight covariates.

(Andreys opinion) Models 2 is the way to go.

Data cleanining

See report 01-phen.html.

  • Several outlier observations were removed.
  • Trait transformation were re-defined (now tr3_ prefix is used for trait names).

h2r ~ model

3 x 42 polygenic models were computed in total.

The first figure shows how different is estimation of h2r depending on model 1, 2 or 3.

The second figure shows results for those models, where Height and/or Weight covariates appeared to be included in model 3.

The third figure shows results for those models, where both Height and Weight covariates appeared to be included in model 3.

It is likely to be suggested that the model of tr3_WBTotFat trait to be discarded from the study. The basic univariate polygenic model has very low h2r, and it could cause problems in furher bivariate studies.
